com.gliffy.restunit.comparator
Class StrictMatchComparator

java.lang.Object
  com.gliffy.restunit.comparator.StrictMatchComparator
All Implemented Interfaces:
ResultComparator
public class StrictMatchComparator
extends Object
implements ResultComparator

A comparator that requires a strict match between received and expected results. This uses the StatusComparator and HeaderComparator to check those portions of the response. The response bodies are compared via compareBodies(byte[],com.gliffy.restunit.http.ContentType,byte[],com.gliffy.restunit.http.ContentType). This implementation requires a byte-for-byte match. You may subclass this and override that method to provide fuzzier matches. You may also wish to override createDiffMessage(byte[],com.gliffy.restunit.http.ContentType,byte[],com.gliffy.restunit.http.ContentType) to create a meaningful diff message.

compareBodies

protected ComparisonResult compareBodies(byte[] expectedBody,
                                         ContentType expectedContentType,
                                         byte[] receivedBody,
                                         ContentType receivedContentType)
Compares the two bodies, requiring an exact match.

Parameters:
expectedBody - the body expected, may be null
expectedContentType - the content type expected by the test, or null if it wasn't specified
receivedBody - the body received, may be null
receivedContentType - the content type received in the response, or null if it wasn't specified
Returns:
a successful match if both bodies are byte-for-byte matches. a null body and an empty body (0-length array) are considered equal. Note that if the content type expected is a text-based type the message included in the ComparisonResult will attempt to render both bits of data as strings, for purposes of indicating the difference. This will be done using the encoding's specified, or the default encoding if none is specified.

createDiffMessage

protected String createDiffMessage(byte[] expectedBody,
                                   ContentType expectedContentType,
                                   byte[] receivedBody,
                                   ContentType receivedContentType)
Given two differing bytestreams, and the content types attached to each, returns a string-based diff message that can help the tester understand why the comparison failed.

Parameters:
expectedBody - the body expected, will not be null (nulls from server get converted to empty arrays)
expectedContentType - the content type expected by the test, or null if it wasn't specified
receivedBody - the body received, will not be null (nulls from server get converted to empty arrays)
receivedContentType - the content type received in the response, or null if it wasn't specified
Returns:
a human-readable message explaining why the comparison failed. This version checks to see if the expected content type is a text-based type. If so, it attempts to convert the bytestreams to strings using the encodings specified in their content types. If the expectedContentType has no encoding the receivedContentType's encoding is used. If no encodings were detected, the system default is used. You should probably write your tests with encodings because of this.
